---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Hero from '../components/Hero.astro';
import About from '../components/About.astro';
import Project from '../components/Project.astro';
import Decision from '../components/Decision.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---
<Base title="Andrew Spiezio">
  <Nav />
  <Hero />
  <About />

  <div class="container">
    <div class="projects-head" id="work">
      <h2>Selected work.</h2>
      <span class="count mono">02 · projects</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <Project
    number="01"
    year="2025 — present"
    title="Judge."
    tag="A diagnostic console for cash recyclers, used daily by field service technicians."
    stack={["FastAPI", "React · TypeScript", "Azure App Service", "SQLite · Redis", "Azure AD / Easy Auth"]}
  >
    <p>
      Built solo since February. Judge turns 1,150+ pages of vendor error documentation into a
      searchable, schematic-aware interface —
      <strong>tap an error code, see the part on the machine</strong>. Two product lines (RBG-100, GLR-100),
      driven by a single configuration so adding a third would be config-only.
    </p>
    <p>
      Underneath the obvious: 60+ guided repair workflows with 460+ field-captured photos,
      prerequisite chains auto-extracted from vendor PDFs, an admin annotation editor, and a
      940-test pre-ship gate before every Azure deploy.
    </p>
    <Decision>
      To make Judge sellable to other service companies, I hardened the security top to bottom —
      single sign-on for every user, a tamper-evident audit log that proves nobody quietly
      edited yesterday's records, per-customer access rules, abuse rate limits, and a startup
      check that refuses to run unless the data is sitting on encrypted disk.
    </Decision>
  </Project>

  <Project
    number="02"
    year="2025"
    title="Custos."
    tag="A cross-platform CLI for talking to tabletop bill counters over USB."
    stack={["Python", "USB · serial", "Cross-platform CLI", "Optional web GUI"]}
  >
    <p>
      Glory bill counters and validators ship with Windows-only vendor software — and nothing
      for talking to the device any other way. Custos opens that up:
      <strong>two-way serial I/O over USB, device enumeration, scriptable commands</strong>. Before
      Custos there was no way to script against these counters at all.
    </p>
    <p>
      Ships as a single CLI binary with an optional web GUI for techs who'd rather click than type.
      Used internally for bench diagnostics; the same plumbing will power the next layer of
      automation we're building on top.
    </p>
  </Project>

  <Footer />
</Base>
